Nigeria will participate in the African Weightlifting Championships slated for April 1 to April 8 at Vacoas in Mauritius, an official said on Wednesday in Abuja. Christopher Nwadei, the Technical Director of Nigeria Weightlifting Federation (NWF), told the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) the tournament would serve as an Olympic qualifier. He said the country’s weightlifters have been preparing for the competition since last year in order to put up a good performance at the championships. ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! “They were in camp in Abuja in December, and they will resume the second phase of the camping programme after the 20th National Sports Festival (NSF) in Edo. “Our target is to win more medals, and gather enough points that will give us the opportunity to feature at the Olympics. The lifters will do their best to make the country proud. Absence Of Judge Stalls Oyo-Ita’s Trial COVID-19: Onuesoke Foundation Kick-Starts Awareness Campaign With Distribution Of 100,000 Face Masks, Sanitisers “We have been putting up good performances whenever we go out to represent the country,” Nwadei said. He added that eight weightlifters —- six  female and two male —- will represent the country at the championships.(NAN)